{"id":"1906.10210","submitter":"Yogesh Madhavrao Chukewad","authors":"Hari Krishna Hari Prasad, Ravi Sankar Vaddi, Yogesh M Chukewad, Elma\n  Dedic, Igor Novosselov, and Sawyer B Fuller","title":"A laser-microfabricated electrohydrodynamic thruster for\n  centimeter-scale aerial robots","comments":"Co-primary authors: Hari Krishna Hari Prasad, Ravi Sankar Vaddi, and\n  Yogesh M Chukewad Submitted to PLOS ONE","journal-ref":"2020","doi":"10.1371/journal.pone.0238267","report-no":"PLoS ONE 15(4): e0231362","categories":"cs.RO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  To date, insect scale robots capable of controlled flight have used flapping\nwings for generating lift, but this requires a complex and failure-prone\nmechanism. A simpler alternative is electrohydrodynamic (EHD) thrust, which\nrequires no moving mechanical parts. In EHD, corona discharge generates a flow\nof ions in an electric field between two electrodes; the high-velocity ions\ntransfer their kinetic energy to neutral air molecules through collisions,\naccelerating the gas and creating thrust. We introduce a fabrication process\nfor EHD thruster based on 355 nm laser micromachining and our approach allows\nfor greater flexibility in materials selection. Our four-thruster device\nmeasures 1.8 x 2.5 cm and is composed of steel emitters and a lightweight\ncarbon fiber mesh. The current and thrust characteristics of each individual\nthruster of the quad thruster is determined and agrees with Townsend relation.\nThe mass of the quad thruster is 37 mg and the measured thrust is greater than\nits weight (362.6 uN). The robot is able to lift off at a voltage of 4.6 kV\nwith a thrust to weight ratio of 1.38.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 24 Jun 2019 20:03:37 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 8 Jul 2019 05:04:18 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 25 Jul 2019 23:46:02 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 15 Jan 2020 02:48:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"202