{"id":"1907.01890","submitter":"Peter Wills","authors":"John S. McCaskill and Peter R.Wills","title":"On permutations derived from integer powers $x^n$","comments":"16 Pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a general theorem characterizing the relationship between the\nprime base $p$ representations of non-negative integers $x$ and their positive\ninteger powers, $x^n$. For any positive integer $l$, the theorem establishes\nthe existence of bijective mappings (permutations) between all $p^l$ members\n$x$ of each non-zero residue class mod $p$ satisfying $x < p^{l+1}$. These\nmappings are obtained as the integer part of ${x^p}{p^{-\\alpha}}$ for a\nparticular positive integer $\\alpha$, depending on $n$ and $p$, called the\n\"coding shift\", for which an explicit formula is given. For relatively prime\n$n$ and $p$, $\\alpha = 1$ and the result follows directly from properties of\nthe multiplicative group of invertible elements modulo $p^{l+1}$. We extend our\nresult for general $n$ also to identify the coding shift required to obtain\nsuch bijective mappings for members of the zero residue class mod $p$,\ndemonstrating that such bijective mappings (or encodings) can be found for any\nfinite $l$ and for all positive integers $x < p^{l+1}$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 25 Jun 2019 14:42:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-04"}
